Task - Trend chart for number of complaints at month level¶

In [4]:
#Create date_index for dataframe
comcast_df['date_index'] = comcast_df['Date_month_year'] + " " + comcast_df['Time']
comcast_df['date_index'] = pd.to_datetime(comcast_df['date_index']) 
comcast_df = comcast_df.set_index(comcast_df['date_index'])

#Plot line chart for Monthly trend of Complaints

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
comcast_df.groupby(pd.Grouper(freq="M")).size().plot(linestyle='--',linewidth=2.0,color='g',marker='o')
plt.title('Number of Complaints by Month')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Number of Complaints')
plt.legend(['Complaint Count'],loc=2)
plt.show()

Task - Trend chart for number of complaints at daily level¶

In [5]:
comcast_df['Date_month_year'] = pd.to_datetime(comcast_df['Date_month_year'])

#Extract Day of month and Day of the week from date column.
comcast_df['Calculated_Day'] = comcast_df['Date_month_year'].apply(lambda x: x.day)
comcast_df['Calculated_DayOfWeek'] = comcast_df['Date_month_year'].apply(lambda x: x.dayofweek)

#Create a dictionary for Day of Week and map the dictionary to Calculated Day of Week
day_dict = {0:'Mon',1:'Tue',2:'Wed',3:'Thur',4:'Fri',5:'Sat',6:'Sun'}
comcast_df['Calculated_DayOfWeek']=comcast_df['Calculated_DayOfWeek'].map(day_dict)
In [6]:
#number of complaints based on created day of the week

plt.figure(figsize=(25,8))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=.25)
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
byweek = comcast_df.groupby('Calculated_DayOfWeek').count().reset_index()
plt.bar('Calculated_DayOfWeek','Customer Complaint',data = byweek,color='g')
plt.xlabel('Day of Week')
plt.title('Number of Complaints by Day of Week')
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
byday = comcast_df.groupby('Calculated_Day').count().reset_index()
plt.plot('Calculated_Day','Customer Complaint',data = byday,color='g')
plt.xlabel('Day fo Month')
plt.ylabel('Number of Complaints')
plt.title('Number of Complaints by Day of Month')
plt.show()

Task-Which Complaint types are maximum ?¶

In [7]:
complaint_words = ''
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)    #pulling in all the words that needs to be ignored from the Customer Complaint
comcast_df['Customer Complaint'] =  comcast_df['Customer Complaint'].apply(lambda x: str(x))
for val in comcast_df['Customer Complaint']:
    tokens = val.split()
    for i in range(len(tokens)):
        tokens[i]=tokens[i].lower()
    complaint_words += " ".join(tokens)+" " 

wordcloud = WordCloud(width = 1000, height = 800,
                background_color ='black',colormap='Set2',
                stopwords = stopwords,
                min_font_size = 10).generate(complaint_words)
 
# plot the WordCloud image                      
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 8), facecolor = None)
plt.imshow(wordcloud)
plt.axis("off")
plt.tight_layout(pad = 0)
 
plt.show()

Task-Create a new column for High level Status pf complaint (Open or Pending in Open and Resolved or Closed in Closed)¶

In [8]:
comcast_df['HighLevelStatus'] = comcast_df['Status'].apply(lambda x: 'Open' if x == 'Open' or x == 'Pending' else ('Closed' if x == 'Closed' or x == 'Solved' else ''))
